l practice and strategy for filmmakers, but it is also a theme of major importance within horror cinema as a hole. The history of the genre is full of adaptations that have drawn from fiction or folklore, or that have assumed the shape of remakes of pre-existing films. The horror genre itself also abounds with its own myriad transformations and transmutations.The essays within this volume engage with an impressive range of horror texts, from the earliest silent horror films by Thomas Edison and Jean Epstein through to important contemporary phenomena, such as the western appropriation of Japanese horror motifs. Classic works by Alfred Hitchcock, David Cronenberg and Abel Ferrara receive cutting-edge re-examination, as do unjustly neglected works by Mario Bava, Guillermo del Toro and Stan Brakhage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aHorror films. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 4aGothic 2017. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aBody Snatchers.  aDr Jekyll and Mr Hyde.  aFrankenstein.  aThe Gorgon.  aVideodrome.  aavant-garde filmmakers.  acinematic experiments.  acorporeal transformation.  ageneric mutations.  amonstrous adaptations.  anarratological re-articulations.  apsychoanalytical theory.  asocietal secularisation.  athematic mutations.  atranscultural adaptations.1 aBlake, Linnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCherry, Brigid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrucianelli, Guy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHand, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHand, Richard, eeditor.4edt